      Buy the rumor, sell the =E2=80=98Weekend Update=E2=80=99 segmentWhen =
Elon Musk does Bitcoin things,  the price of Bitcoin goes up. One possible =
reason for this is that Elon Musk is a rich famous weird guy with a fandom;=
 people pay attention to what he does and get entertainment out of it. When=
 he seems to have fun with Bitcoin, other people say =E2=80=9Chey Bitcoin l=
ooks fun=E2=80=9D and buy Bitcoin, so the price of Bitcoin goes up.Another =
possible reason is that Elon Musk is the chief executive officer of=C2=A0tw=
o big influential futuristic companies, and he plays a role in shaping the =
possible future of the global economy. If Tesla Inc. announced that you can=
 only pay for Teslas in Bitcoin, or if SpaceX announced that the only legal=
 tender on Mars will be Bitcoin, that would be good for Bitcoin demand. The=
re is a sort of future-of-the-galactic-economy case for Bitcoin that Elon M=
usk can bolster. And in fact Tesla has said that it will (non-exclusively) =
accept Bitcoins for Teslas, and that it will keep a portion of its corporat=
e cash in Bitcoin. Tesla, a big important company that Musk runs, is making=
 real business decisions that seem to be bullish for Bitcoin. If you buy Bi=
tcoin based on Musk=E2=80=99s half-joking Twitter enthusiasm, you could be =
making a sensible bet on business fundamentals.When Elon Musk does Dogecoin=
 things =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, look, Dogecoin is  famously a joke, and Elon M=
usk enjoys jokes, and people enjoy following along with Elon Musk=E2=80=99s=
 jokes at home, and so when Elon Musk does a Dogecoin joke Dogecoin goes up=
.=C2=A0There is an obvious =E2=80=9Crich famous weird guy with a fandom=E2=
=80=9D effect.On the other hand, is there a business fundamentals case? Wil=
l Tesla accept Dogecoin as payment? Will it be legal tender on Mars? Sure, =
I dunno, whatever,=C2=A0but on =E2=80=9CSaturday Night Live=E2=80=9D this w=
eekend Musk  leaned hard on the =E2=80=9Cjoke=E2=80=9D side:Dogecoin, the f=
ifth most valuable cryptocurrency, retreated from an all-time high after bi=
llionaire Elon Musk, appearing on =E2=80=9CSaturday Night Live,=E2=80=9D jo=
kingly called it =E2=80=9Ca hustle.=E2=80=9DThe altcoin had surpassed 73 ce=
nts on Saturday before dropping to 46.01 cents as of 8:08 a.m. in New York =
Sunday, a 35% decline in 24 hours, according to pricing from CoinGecko. =E2=
=80=A6Musk was asked repeatedly during the =E2=80=9CWeekend Update=E2=80=9D=
 segment to explain what Dogecoin is. After reciting multiple facts about t=
he cryptocurrency in the character of a financial expert, he was asked if D=
ogecoin was a =E2=80=9Chustle.=E2=80=9D He responded, =E2=80=9Cyeah, it=E2=
=80=99s a hustle.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6An earlier Dogecoin reference came duri=
ng the opening monologue where his mother, Maye Musk, joined him on stage. =
The author and model said she was excited about her Mother=E2=80=99s Day gi=
ft, and she hoped it=E2=80=99s not Dogecoin -- to which he said, =E2=80=9Ci=
t is.=E2=80=9DI want to emphasize again that I understand nothing, but, lik=
e =E2=80=A6=C2=A0if you bet big on Dogecoin heading into =E2=80=9CSaturday =
Night Live,=E2=80=9D and then dumped your Dogecoins because you didn=E2=80=
=99t like what you heard on =E2=80=9CSaturday Night Live,=E2=80=9D what=C2=
=A0were=C2=A0you hoping to hear? Like, =E2=80=9CSaturday Night Live=E2=80=
=9D is a comedy program. Elon Musk was going to make jokes about Dogecoin. =
That was pretty much the best you could hope for, from Elon Musk on =E2=80=
=9CSaturday Night Live,=E2=80=9D if you=E2=80=99re a Dogecoin bull.=C2=A0I =
am sorry but: to the moonUh =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is=C2=A0this=C2=A0what you were =
hoping to hear?Elon Musk=E2=80=99s SpaceX will launch the =E2=80=9CDOGE-1 M=
ission to the Moon=E2=80=9D in the first quarter of 2022, with the company =
accepting the meme-inspired cryptocurrency as full payment for the lunar pa=
yload.Geometric Energy Corporation announced the dogecoin-funded mission on=
 Sunday, which SpaceX=E2=80=99s communications team confirmed in an email t=
o reporters. The mission=E2=80=99s financial value was not disclosed.DOGE-1=
 will fly a 40 kilogram cube satellite as a payload on a Falcon 9 rocket, w=
ith Geometric Energy Corporation saying its payload =E2=80=9Cwill obtain lu=
nar-spatial intelligence from sensors and cameras on-board with integrated =
communications and computational systems.=E2=80=9DSpaceX vice president of =
commercial sales Tom Ochinero said in a statement that DOGE-1 =E2=80=9Cwill=
 demonstrate the application of cryptocurrency beyond Earth orbit and set t=
he foundation for interplanetary commerce.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re e=
xcited to launch DOGE-1 to the Moon!=E2=80=9D Ochinero said.The price went =
back up. Geometric Energy Corp.=C2=A0makes nitrile gloves, does other misce=
llaneous projects, and says =E2=80=9CTransforming Civilization=E2=80=9D at =
the top of its web page. I have to say, I really admire this trade; this is=
 how you do postmodern finance. I think the trade is:=09Accumulate a bunch =
of Dogecoins.=09Go to Elon Musk and say =E2=80=9Chey would you accept payme=
nt in Dogecoins to do a=C2=A0Dogecoin stunt?=E2=80=9D=09Elon Musk is like =
=E2=80=9Csure, I love Dogecoins, and stunts.=E2=80=9D=09You pay him some Do=
gecoins to launch some stuff into space.=09You and he both announce that Sp=
aceX is accepting Dogecoin for payment for a rocket payload that has someth=
ing to do with the moon.[1]=09=E2=80=9CLook: SpaceX is accepting Dogecoin! =
Institutional adoption! Dogecoin is a useful currency! There are applicatio=
ns! Dogecoin will be the official currency of space travel! It will be wide=
ly adopted throughout the galaxy! If you are traveling to Mars you will nee=
d to convert some dollars into Dogecoin!=E2=80=9D You know, that sort of th=
ing.=09The value of your remaining stash of Dogecoins goes up a lot.If you =
have 10 million Dogecoins, what you want to do is=C2=A0spend a million of t=
hem, because demonstrating that you can spend Dogecoins is a good way to pr=
ove that they are useful and thus make the value of your remaining 9 millio=
n Dogecoins go up. What you particularly want to do is=C2=A0spend your Doge=
coins at an Elon Musk store, because that will focus a lot of attention on =
the fact that you can spend Dogecoins, because people pay a lot of attentio=
n to the Elon Musk stores. And you want to spend them on the most high-prof=
ile and stunty Elon Musk store available, which is probably shooting a rock=
et to the moon.Dogecoin is =E2=80=94=C2=A0so much postmodern crypto/GameSto=
p finance is, really =E2=80=94=C2=A0finance with the cash flows abstracted =
away. In traditional finance, you have a=C2=A0thing with some more or less =
uncertain stream of future=C2=A0cash flows, and the value of the thing is t=
he present value of its future cash flows, filtered through some large amou=
nt of uncertainty and psychology and behavior and greed and fear and techni=
cal factors and fund flows etc. The skill set is some combination of unders=
tanding the cash flows and understanding the psychology.In postmodern finan=
ce the psychology is the only thing. For sort of accidental path-dependence=
 reasons, the people making fortunes in this world are often=C2=A0finance=
=C2=A0people, quant traders who saw the rise of crypto and thought =E2=80=
=9Cthat=E2=80=99s like what I do now, but without any fundamentals,=E2=80=
=9D and who jumped on it. Fine. But it is not obvious that this is the righ=
t, or only, skill set. Really if postmodern finance is primarily a matter o=
f=C2=A0mass psychology, isn=E2=80=99t it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0marketing? Advertis=
ing? Isn=E2=80=99t the right skill set not, like, =E2=80=9Cidentify technic=
al patterns in charts=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Cthink of good stunts tha=
t will make people want to buy a content-free product that you happen to be=
 selling=E2=80=9D? If you are a Dogecoin trader and you=E2=80=99re not spen=
ding some Dogecoins to get Elon Musk to put out a press release with the wo=
rds =E2=80=9CDogecoin=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cmoon=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Crock=
et=E2=80=9D in it, you might be doing it wrong.Elsewhere in Elon MuskWell t=
here=E2=80=99s this:Tesla CEO Elon Musk has been overstating the capabiliti=
es of the company=E2=80=99s advanced driver assist system, the company=E2=
=80=99s director of Autopilot software told the California Department of Mo=
tor Vehicles. The comments came from a memo released by legal transparency =
group PlainSite, which obtained the documents from a public records request=
. ...=E2=80=9CElon=E2=80=99s tweet does not match engineering reality per C=
J. Tesla is at Level 2 currently,=E2=80=9D the California DMV said in the m=
emo about its March 9th conference call with Tesla representatives, includi=
ng the director of Autopilot software CJ Moore. Level 2 technology refers t=
o a semi-automated driving system, which requires supervision by a human dr=
iver.=C2=A0In an earnings call in January, Musk told investors that he was =
=E2=80=9Chighly confident the car will be able to drive itself with reliabi=
lity in excess of human this year.=E2=80=9D (It would appear the DMV was re=
ferring to these January comments, which Moore misunderstood as a tweet fro=
m Musk.) =E2=80=A6Tesla is unlikely to achieve Level 5 (L5) autonomy, in wh=
ich its cars can drive themselves anywhere, under any conditions, without a=
ny human supervision, by the end of 2021, Tesla representatives told the DM=
V.Is this securities fraud? Meh. We have talked a lot recently about the no=
tion that influential visionary startup founders are expected to do a certa=
in amount of optimistic truth-stretching,=C2=A0that seeing the future so cl=
early that you convince yourself it=E2=80=99s here already is part of the j=
ob. Occasionally actual startup founders  get in trouble for this. Other ti=
mes, startup founders take their companies public, and then  can=E2=80=99t =
adapt to their new, more factual obligations as public-company CEOs. And th=
en there=E2=80=99s Elon Musk, who just gets to keep talking like a visionar=
y startup founder even though he runs a giant public company.I think the tr=
ick is to say=C2=A0so much=C2=A0nonsense that anyone who focuses on one par=
ticular untrue statement looks a little silly: =E2=80=9CSure I said our car=
s would be fully self-driving this year, and that wasn=E2=80=99t true, but =
I tweet like 10 crazy jokes a day, why would anyone believe me?=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0Oh also Musk is a meme thief: People make jokes on the internet, and Mus=
k reposts them to his accounts without attribution. I don=E2=80=99t really =
know what to make of this. On the one hand, Musk is a busy guy, running two=
 futuristic companies and pumping cryptocurrencies and doing sketch comedy =
on national television; I suppose it=E2=80=99s good that he steals memes fr=
om the internet rather than carefully handcrafting them himself. (Obviously=
 it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0rude, mean to creators, etc., but equally obviously he d=
oesn=E2=80=99t care about other people and getting mad at him for stealing =
memes won=E2=80=99t change anything.)On the other hand, Musk is a busy guy,=
 running two futuristic companies etc.; doesn=E2=80=99t he have better thin=
gs to do than=C2=A0steal memes?=C2=A0Ugh, no, I guess=C2=A0my theory of Elo=
n Musk compels me to say that the most value he can add to his companies =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0more than dreaming up new cars or rockets, or finding good a=
cquisitions or optimizing the capital structure or hiring talented managers=
 or whatever other normal-CEO things he sometimes does =E2=80=94=C2=A0is by=
 tweeting the good tweets. I  once wrote that the optimal use of time for a=
 modern CEO might be to =E2=80=9Cdo good tweets to get a lot of fans on the=
 internet, who will buy the stock for the lols and maximize the stock price=
=E2=80=9D:There will be academic papers and Harvard Business School case st=
udies about how CEOs who tweet a lot of nonsense=C2=A0maximize shareholder =
value; it will become a conventional part of the business school curriculum=
; a generation of CEOs will grow up just assuming that being weird edgelord=
s online is not just fun but also=C2=A0their legal and moral obligation as =
fiduciaries for their shareholders.And if the most efficient way to do the =
good tweets is by stealing content from other users, well, that=E2=80=99s j=
ust capitalism I guess.Oh and: =E2=80=9CGerman engineer predicted man named=
 =E2=80=98Elon=E2=80=99 would conquer Mars in 1952 novel,=E2=80=9D why not.=
Sovereign bond allocationsWe are spending a lot of time on dumb crypto thin=
gs so let=E2=80=99s take a break and talk about a dumb traditional high-fin=
ance thing. Here is a Wall Street Journal story about sovereign bond alloca=
tions:European governments are acting to limit hedge funds=E2=80=99 partici=
pation in the market for new sovereign bond issuance, following a surge in =
demand from the firms.The pushback was prompted by unusually large orders p=
laced by hedge funds for new bonds, which can then potentially be sold=E2=
=80=94sometimes within hours=E2=80=94to the European Central Bank for a pro=
fit, bankers, investors and a government official said. Order books, which =
track demand for new bonds and help determine the prices, have ballooned si=
nce hedge funds began to pile into this trade.The debt-management offices o=
f Spain and Italy have placed caps ranging from 500 million euros to 1 bill=
ion euros, equivalent to $608 million to $1.2 billion, on orders from hedge=
 funds for bonds directly issued by countries in the primary market, accord=
ing to bankers who worked on the deals. France has also limited order sizes=
, an official said.Millennium Management, Brevan Howard, DoubleLine, Tenaro=
n Capital Management and BlueBay Asset Management are among the hedge funds=
 that have been active in the primary market for sovereign bonds in recent =
months, according to bankers. Some hedge funds have put in orders for as mu=
ch as 3 billion euros of bonds in a single offering, which is far more than=
 they can realistically buy, the bankers said.So there are two dumb things =
here. One is that the hedge funds=E2=80=99 trade is just:=09Buy new-issue E=
uropean government bonds.=09Sell them immediately to the ECB.There are good=
 historical and institutional reasons that the ECB doesn=E2=80=99t buy new-=
issue=C2=A0bonds directly from the governments of member states (=E2=80=9Cm=
onetizing the debt,=E2=80=9D bad), but the result is that now it buys them =
indirectly from hedge funds. The hedge funds are effectively getting paid a=
 commission for helping the ECB do a regulatory arbitrage: It can=E2=80=99t=
 buy new-issue bonds, it wants to buy new-issue bonds, so it buys almost-ne=
w-issue bonds from hedge funds for a small markup. This is a little dumb =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0why waste money on paying hedge funds? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=
 is in the ordinary line of high-finance dumbness. One very standard busine=
ss line for hedge funds is helping regulated entities offload regulatory di=
fficulties, for a fee, and you can think of this in the same terms.The othe=
r dumb thing has to do with how new-issue securities are sold. You might im=
agine a system like this:=09An issuer announces how much of a thing it want=
s to sell and a rough price range. =E2=80=9CWe want to sell 1 billion thing=
s at a range of 97 to 103.=E2=80=9D=09Its banks canvass potential buyers to=
 market the thing.=09The potential buyers submit a demand schedule of how m=
uch of the thing they=E2=80=99d like to buy at various price points: =E2=80=
=9CWe won=E2=80=99t buy it for 102 or above, we=E2=80=99d buy a million of =
it at 101, we=E2=80=99d buy 2 million at 100, we=E2=80=99d buy 3 million at=
 99 or below,=E2=80=9D etc.[2]=09The issuer and its banks look at the sched=
ule of demand: =E2=80=9CWe have orders for 1.86 billion at 99, 1.31 billion=
 at 100, 1.04 billion at 101, 956 million at 102,=E2=80=9D etc.=09They pric=
e the thing at the highest price at which there is enough demand to get the=
 size they want: Here, there's 1.04 billion of demand at 101, and they want=
 to sell 1 billion, so they price at 101.This is an easy system to imagine,=
 and everyone does=C2=A0imagine it. The process for most initial public off=
erings of stock does=C2=A0kind of=C2=A0work like this, in a rough and imper=
fect way. Every so often an issuer will be like =E2=80=9Cwhat if we made it=
 work more like that,=E2=80=9D and you get things like the  Google IPO (a D=
utch auction where investors submitted orders at prices) or the =E2=80=9C h=
ybrid IPO=E2=80=9D (where investors submit a full schedule of demand and th=
e issuer looks at it to pick a price) or even direct listings (where there=
=E2=80=99s a two-sided auction to pick the opening price).=C2=A0These proce=
sses are not perfect, though; there are IPO pops, etc., and people complain=
 a lot.The way=C2=A0bond new issues often work, though, is sort of like thi=
s:=09An issuer announces how much of a bond it wants to sell and a rough pr=
ice. =E2=80=9CWe want to sell 1 billion bonds at about 1%,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0et=
c.=09Its banks canvass potential buyers.=09The potential buyers say =E2=80=
=9Cwe=E2=80=99d buy 1 million=E2=80=9D or whatever.=09The issuer and its ba=
nks look at the total amount of demand and pick a price out of =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0thin air? Like, if the issuer has 10 billion of orders, it will say =E2=
=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s pretty good, let=E2=80=99s price at 0.95%=E2=80=9D; if=
 it has 1.01 billion of orders it will say =E2=80=9Chmm, cutting it close, =
let=E2=80=99s price at 1.05%.=E2=80=9D=09If there=E2=80=99s a lot of demand=
, the issuer will price at a low interest rate =E2=80=94=C2=A00.95% or what=
ever =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the people who put in orders thinking the bond woul=
d price at 1% will be surprised.=09Some of them will withdraw their orders =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe would have bought 1 million at 1%, but not at 0.=
95%=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the issuer and bankers will get mad at them=
, because that is viewed as not sporting. Your order is supposed to be your=
 order, no matter what the price is.I find this very weird! Yet it is sort =
of the norm. From the Journal:The recent surge of interest from hedge funds=
 in the primary market is making it difficult to price the bonds, as it is =
more difficult to gauge the real demand, said Benjamin de Forton, a debt-ca=
pital markets director at BNP Paribas.For instance, Spain attracted 130 bil=
lion euros of orders for a 10-year bond offering in January. But as bankers=
 hammered out the final terms of the sale and the proposed price climbed, d=
emand for the bonds abruptly halved. That was because hedge funds pulled th=
eir orders as their already slim profit margins shrank, bankers said. The g=
overnment ultimately raised 10 billion euros, with the bulk of the buyers b=
eing traditional asset managers. Hedge funds got about 5.5% of the bonds so=
ld, bankers on the deal said.=E2=80=9CSwift moves in fast-money account ord=
ers have meant new-bond execution was at times potentially more challenging=
,=E2=80=9D Mr. de Forton said.Yeah, I don=E2=80=99t know, I sympathize a lo=
t with the hedge funds there? Why not just ask them? Instead of sending the=
m a form like =E2=80=9Chow many bonds would you like,=E2=80=9D send them a =
form like =E2=80=9Chow many bonds would you like at different prices?=E2=80=
=9D Build a schedule of demand and then use it to price your bonds.The othe=
r problem is that there is a self-reinforcing thing where issuers take orde=
rs for more bonds than they are selling, and so investors don=E2=80=99t get=
 as many bonds as they ask for, and so they put in larger orders to try to =
get more bonds, and so they get cut back even more, etc.:Banks that run deb=
t sales for governments tend to allocate less than 10% of an issuance to he=
dge funds. The firms typically receive only around 1% of what they offer to=
 buy, which encourages them to place large orders, according to bankers. Th=
at means an offer to buy about 2 billion euros in bonds could net the hedge=
 funds about 20 million euros of the securities. ...France=E2=80=99s debt m=
anagement office asked banks in March to hold talks with hedge funds to enc=
ourage them to put in smaller orders, according to Anthony Requin, chief ex=
ecutive of the agency. Firms that put in unrealistically large orders would=
 be penalized with a smaller allocation than other firms that put in more =
=E2=80=9Creasonable orders,=E2=80=9D he said.These problems interact: If a =
hedge fund wants 20 million bonds at 1% or higher, it will put in an order =
for 2 billion bonds, but if the price goes up so the yield is below 1% it w=
ill pull that whole order:=E2=80=9CThe relationship between what could be c=
onsidered as a good transaction and the sheer size of the order book is bro=
ken,=E2=80=9D said Mr. Requin. =E2=80=9COne may be confronted with a skyroc=
keting order book, but which is in fact of poor quality. In that case, tigh=
tening the price might be challenging or risky if you are targeting a trans=
action of [a] certain size.=E2=80=9DThese just feel like solvable problems.=
 The U.S. Treasury, it should be said,=C2=A0auctions its bonds, which seems=
 to work?SocksThe way that non-fungible tokens often work is:=09You acquire=
 some physical object, ideally a rare or unique one, perhaps a work of art.=
=09You light it on fire.=09You create a video recording of the destruction =
of the object, or at least type up a certificate saying =E2=80=9CI destroye=
d this object.=E2=80=9D=09You encode the video or the certificate on a bloc=
kchain, as a unique immutable token.=09You sell the token to someone else, =
for more than you paid for the object.I do not pretend to understand it eit=
her, but we have talked a  couple of  times about this basic =E2=80=9Cobjec=
t =E2=80=94=C2=A0fire =E2=80=94=C2=A0token =E2=80=94=C2=A0money=E2=80=9D NF=
T cycle and it is, if not the default, at least=C2=A0one=C2=A0standard way =
to make and sell and understand NFTs. You remove an art object from circula=
tion in the physical world and circulate it instead in the blockchain world=
, for more money.One way to think about this process might be that the fire=
, and the encoding on the blockchain,=C2=A0adds value. A painting is worth =
$100,000, but a painting that has been burnt to ashes and put on the blockc=
hain is worth $200,000, in the same way that flour and eggs and sugar are w=
orth $3, but if you combine them in the oven and make=C2=A0a cake it is=C2=
=A0worth $6. You have taken some ingredients (a work of art, a lighter, a v=
ideo camera) and combined them with your labor to make something more usefu=
l and desirable. I am typing this theory here for completeness, but it does=
 not strike me as at all plausible.The more plausible way to think about th=
is process might be one of market segmentation and arbitrage. There are som=
e people who like paintings and will pay $X for a painting.  There are othe=
r people who like NFTs and will pay $Y for a token of a burnt painting. Whe=
n X > Y =E2=80=94=C2=A0as, loosely speaking, it has been for most of human =
history =E2=80=94=C2=A0people will keep paintings intact. When Y > X =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0as it seems to have been recently during a wild NFT boom =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0people will burn paintings to sell them as higher-value NFTs.[3]On th=
e other hand, if X > Y again =E2=80=94=C2=A0if the NFT market cools and pai=
ntings are worth more than tokens again =E2=80=94=C2=A0it would be nice to =
have a way to transform the tokens back into paintings. Take the NFTs, ligh=
t them on fire, have a painting come out, and sell the painting for more th=
an you paid for the NFT. Just as a matter of market completeness one wants =
this to be possible, to be able to trade frictionlessly between physical ob=
jects and their blockchain representations. Financial processes  ought to b=
e reversible.Unfortunately, for reasons of physics, it is very difficult to=
 reverse the =E2=80=9Cobject =E2=80=94=C2=A0fire =E2=80=94=C2=A0token =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0money=E2=80=9D NFT process, because if you light a token on fir=
e you cannot get the original painting back.[4] You cannot burn tokens to g=
et back paintings.You can, however, burn tokens to get back socks. Here are=
=C2=A0Unisocks, which are socks that trade on the Uniswap crypto platform:$=
SOCKS is a token that entitles you to 1 real pair of limited edition socks,=
 shipped anywhere in the world.You can sell the token back at any time. To =
get a real pair, redeem a $SOCKS token.=E2=80=9CSOCKS will be burned in exc=
hange for 1 real pair of unisocks + shipping to anywhere in the world,=E2=
=80=9D said Uniswap Labs when it announced the socks in 2019, so, yes, you =
could burn tokens for socks.[5]=C2=A0As of 10 a.m. today, the SOCKS token w=
as trading at about $99,000. So a tokenized pair of limited-edition socks w=
as worth $99,000. People would=C2=A0pay $99,000 for a non-wearable blockcha=
in representation of a pair of socks.Is that more or less than they=E2=80=
=99d pay for the physical, wearable=C2=A0socks? Well, look. For one thing, =
you can get very nice socks for less than $20, though that tells you nothin=
g; these socks are an art project/collectible/stunt, so whether you buy the=
m in token form or sock form you are mostly paying for some sort of intangi=
ble prestige. For another thing, I think it is reasonable to say that if so=
me crypto startup =E2=80=94=C2=A0or some movie star or musician or athlete =
or Elon Musk or any other conveyer of prestige for that matter =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0just announced a limited edition of 500 pairs of socks, those socks woul=
d not trade for $99,000.[6] You have to transmute the socks through the NFT=
 first.=C2=A0On the other hand, once you have done that, maybe the socks ar=
e worth more than the token? Apparently yesterday someone=C2=A0burned=C2=A0=
nine pairs=E2=80=99 worth of SOCKS tokens, for socks. (The token was worth =
about $97,000 at the time.) They looked at the price of the tokens, thought=
 about the socks, and decided that they=E2=80=99d rather have the socks. To=
 put in their trophy case, or to re-sell for more than $97,000, or, of cour=
se, to wear around the house. The object =E2=80=94=C2=A0fire =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0token =E2=80=94=C2=A0money process is reversible; the market is complete=
.Eventually I will write the dumbest possible Money Stuff and then sell it =
as an NFT. I don=E2=80=99t think we are there yet but we are getting very c=
